description:
From its iconic imagery, stars and score, MGM's "Man with no Name" trilogy is a modern masterpiece of cinema! And now, the legend comes to life once again as the next new series from Dynamite!

Starring the ultimate anti-hero, and under the helm of writer Christos (New Avengers) Gage and artist Wellington Dias, MAN WITH NO NAME: THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UGLIER #1 follows in the powerful wake of such Dynamite titles as The Lone Ranger and Zorro in its faithful and successful genre-defining Western comics! Plus: MAN WITH NO NAME: THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UGLIER #1 follows the characters and plots of the film serving as a sequel to the critically acclaimed series!

Featuring series covers by Richard (Dark Tower) Isanove as well as a special 1-10 altenrate "zombie" cover by Arthur Suydam, Dynamite's MAN WITH NO NAME: THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UGLIER #1 is the next bullet in the chamber for 2008!
name: The Man With No Name

description:
In Rann/Thanagar: Holy War old hostilities and new religions clash as war is declared! Nothing will ever be the same when Lady Styx returns to finish her conversion of Rann—but will those who now worship her attempt to stop her tyranny? At the same time Deacon Dark unleashes a plot that defines a major new evil in the DCU and brings the Church of Eternal Light into direct conflict with Styx. As usual, our heroes are stuck in the middle of a bad situation as Adam Strange, Hawkman, Animal Man, Starfire, Comet, the L.E.G.I.O.N. and more try desperately to stop the conflict.

Rann/Thanagar: Holy War is an 8-issue series brought to you by Jim Starlin and Ron Lim. They have plenty of twists and turns planned, so get ready to see new characters, some surprise guests, and find out if this is a war that can only end in tragedy. And don't forget to read:

Adam Strange Special and Hawkman Special.
name: Rann/Thanagar Holy War

description:
The magazine known as Miss America started out as Miss America Comic, which only lasted one issue before the comic was changed to a magazine format. From the second issue on, the focus of the book was more on teenage romance story's then actual superhero story's. The second issue of Miss America also featured the first appearance of Patsy Walker, whom would later take a large role in the book, and eventually take the whole series over.

All together, Miss America Magazine ran 83 issues in total. It had a complicated numbering with a new volume that was put in the indica every few years, continuing up until vol. 7, issue 50 (better known as the 83rd issue of Miss America Magazine). After that issue, the series reverted back to a comic book format as Miss America, and started numbering with issue 51 (witch followed the numbering of 'vol. 7" of the Magazine).
name: Miss America Magazine
